 <br>
Dartmoor: While this was considered to be one of the three “Epic Zones” at release, the difficulty is now sub-par compared to more recent areas. The loot was marginal at best until the most recent patch, 1.60, which increased the Bonus % on old area loot significantly. If you’re looking for easy to obtain level 50, 35% bonus items, these should be available in Dartmoor now. Most items are only 90% quality, however, so larger groups wouldn’t have much to gain. <br>
 <br>
Moran the Mighty: Moran isn’t terribly difficult anymore, especially considering the fact that he is rarely killed outside of dragon raids. Nevertheless, if someone would like to fight him outside one of these raids, he does drop 0-2 items on a moderately frequent basis. One to two groups of level 50s are probably quite enough for this encounter. It’s easiest to use a relog puller and get the adds first, then focus on Moran. <br>
 <br>
“Standard” Dartmoor Named Monsters: These monsters are usually slightly more difficult than a non-named of their type, and drop a single random Dartmoor item. Beyond that, they do not appear to have any unusual qualities. <br>
 <br>
Golestandt: This is the final boss of Dartmoor, and the Mainland dragon for Albion. I have had more failures than successes against Golestandt, however, most of my raids were not recent by any standards (most were before there were Realm Abilities or Epic Armor, for example). My successes (I’ve had four) had a number of players ranging between 125 and 160. In the case of one of my smaller raids, we also had almost all of the relics. I have not run any raids on Golestandt since the recent decrease in Epic Monster resistances, but he did seem significantly easier to affect on the raids I attended after this time. <br>
 <br>
General Tactics to use: Resurrection Groups, Debuffs, Zerging, Pet Spam. <br>
Specific Tactics to use: Golestandt will patrol approximately once per hour (this number may be way off, I haven’t sat around and observed it). During this time, he will come near several of the entrances of his “Keep”, so be sure to try to avoid those areas. This is a good time to try to clear the giants inside his keep – there are typically four, one in each of the four corners. The four entrances to his keep are in the center of each of the directional sides, so they aren’t hard to find. I typically place one group at the north side, and divide my forces evenly over the other three entrances. When the giants are clear, I have the north side charge first. <br>
The north side is simply a distraction to draw aggro, and potentially eat the breath weapon. The chance to use the breath weapon seems highest on the initial approach, since Golestandt tends to breathe more frequently when the target he aggro on is at range. Balena observed this on the Guinevere server, and it seems to hold true. All players should be charging into melee range of the dragon, but they should not all be meleeing. Characters can do whatever they please – the rumors of spellcasting, archery, and the like triggering dragon breath are false. These seem to have primarily sprung from the fact that Golestandt does seem to use his breath more when targeting someone at range, and typically spellcasters and archers attack at a distance. As such, procing weapons do not necessarily need to be avoided. Last I checked, heat damage does not heal Golestandt, but it isn’t terribly effective either. <br>
If possible, most of the fighting should be taking place under Golestandt, or behind him from within melee range. Pet Spam is extremely helpful for increasing hit rate and giving Golestandt additional melee targets. The way his breath weapon is coded now, I’m fairly sure he’ll still use it in melee, just infrequently. Constantly moving seems to lessen the damage from his breath weapon, as you will typically be transitioning in and out of range. Golestandt also has several other special abilities. Throwing players into the air will deal them falling damage, and is typically the least deadly. Golestandt also teleports players to nearby areas of the zone fairly frequently now – this is an annoyance as well as a potential problem if Golestandt re-aggroes on these players as they charge in, since this may trigger another use of his breath weapon. <br>
At low health, Golestandt frequently uses a Point Blank Area of Effect (PBAOE) stun spell, which will stun all attackers in melee range for about thirty seconds. Purge is an effective counter, if available. He also calls for help – I would highly suggest that if he calls Giants, they are cleared first, as their damage dealing capabilities are high and they will fall much faster than Golestandt himself. <br>
Rewards: Four 100% Quality “Dragon Items”, Twelve “Normal” Dartmoor items, and 50 Respec Stones. <br>
 <br>
<br>
Lyonesse: Another of the “Old” zones, this area benefits from the same loot upgrade as Dartmoor, as well as some new monsters for standard hunting. The “trees” and “pygmy goblin” camps here are extremely popular for hunting at high levels. The loot in the zone is of comparable quality to Dartmoor, as they were itemized simultaneously. Overall, due to how well the spawns are spread out and how easily controlled and predicted the BAF can be, this can be an excellent zone to hunt in for experience. <br>
 <br>
Callieach Urgaig: I consider this to be a “fun” encounter. It’s used for one of the Epic Quests now, and her drop rate seems to have been decreased since that time. Callieach is usually a one to two group encounter, with less players necessary if Relog pulling is used. Typically, she can be pulled alone if one side of the area she is in is pulled before she is. She calls for help at low health, however, and this can be extremely painful for a small group of players. In addition, the four pillars surrounding her will shoot fireballs from the top. These fireballs deal low damage, and are supposedly something from her father, Mithras, to protect her. <br>
Rewards for Callieach Urgaig: Celestial Cailiondar armor, which pre-Epic, was some of the best in the game. The armor AF100, with 94% quality and excellent statistics, however, she only drops Breastplates. Pre-Epic, she had a drop rate of about 50% overall. Presumably, the Bonus% on these items has now been increased to 35% from 25%, but I can’t confirm that yet. <br>
 <br>
Sister Blythe: Not much outstanding about this mob, just be well aware she hits like a truck (700+ per hit, if I recall). No unique loot at the time that I hunted her, but she may be itemized by now. She is also part of an Epic Quest. <br>
 <br>
Llyn Barfog: There are six “Epic Monsters” in Llyn Barfog, all of which are fairly easy by current standards. There also are several high level places to hunt now, with loot comparable to Dartmoor and Lyonesse, but with “Charges” on the weapons. <br>
 <br>
Mouth: One of the easier Epic Monsters, but they seem to have a large spawn level range or some other variable that affects their difficulty somewhat. <br>
 <br>
King of Barfog Hills: Generally considered to be the easiest of the “Barfog Epics”. <br>
 <br>
Fester: Fester has a fast attack rate, but low health. They typically drop mage items, such as cloth and focus staves. <br>
 <br>
Teaz—(Can’t remember the spelling =P): High defense and damage, slow attack rate. Moderate overall difficulty. <br>
 <br>
Afanc: Afanc is the second hardest “Epic Monster” in Llyn Barfog, and while even a small group or even a duo or trio with a Cabalist focus damage shield can easily defeat most of the other monsters, Afanc typically works best with a full group. Their melee damage is extremely high (over a thousand), which makes healing and pet damage shield tactics difficult in many cases. <br>
 <br>
Wrath of Mordred: Mordred is the most difficult “Epic Monster” in Llyn Barfog. He parries, frequently “double hits”, and procs a direct damage spell for approximately 800 damage. These factors mean that the cabalist focus damage shield isn’t terribly effective. Depending on how difficult Mordred’s current spawn is, one group or more is suggested. <br>
Rewards: Seems to be about a 50%+ chance of dropping a single item for the first four Epics, with a slightly higher chance for Mordred and Afanc, and chance for Mordred and Afanc to drop two (or possibly even three) items. Afanc’s loot seems to be randomly chosen from the loot tables of all of the other Epics, as well as a few items of his own, particularly cloaks. Mordred drops Plate Mail and two-handed weapons. Note that Llyn Barfog weapons lack particle effects, making them less attractive than Dartmoor or Darkness Falls ones. All Barfog Epic items are 93% Quality, and pre-1.60, they were 30% bonus. Presumably, this bonus % has been increased to 35% now. <br>
 <br>
Halls of the Corrupt: This area has items created by the Random Object Generator (ROG) system. As such, the loot Quality and Bonus% are unreliable, but potentially powerful items are possible. Statistics on the items also many not be optimum, as you may find statistics meant for more than one character class on any given item. The zone’s difficulty is moderate, and it is primarily meant as a method of reaching the other “RvR Dungeons” and the central area between them, the “Summoner’s Hall”. <br>
 <br>
Archwizard: A fairly difficult boss, good for about two groups, in my experience. During the fight, he will split and make weaker duplicates of himself. Only the real wizard will drop items, however. <br>
Rewards: Fairly mediocre. Not sure what the quality is if he has any unique drops, I only remember seeing ROG items. <br>
 <br>
Summoner’s Hall: I don’t know this area well enough to really comment at this time. <br>
 <br>
Grand Summoner: Quite difficult, a good fight for approximately four to five full groups. Since his aggro can be held on a single target, it’s possible to kill him with fewer players, but much more time consuming. He will change his form when he loses about 35% of his health, but this change appears to primarily be cosmetic. He parries, so it’s good to keep most attackers behind him. He is also capable of healing himself and a few other minor spells. <br>
Rewards: The Grand Summoner’s item drops are 93% quality – not sufficient to be worth the effort, in my opinion. The Grand Summoner’s Silken Mantle, his cloak, is one of the best in the game, however. This item alone makes hunting him worthwhile in many cases. <br>
 <br>
Pennine Mountains: A fairly good hunting area in the Albion frontier. The drop quality tends to be 89%, which is mediocre at best for high levels, but the experience is pretty good and the area has some interesting monsters. Good for variety, and protecting the keeps there, but not the best hunting zone in Albion overall. Hadrian’s Wall is a similar story. <br>
 <br>
Ellyl Lord: This is an Epic Quest monster, and he doesn’t seem to have much other use or reward. Ellyls do have a particle effect longsword that they occasionally drop, however, and a few other items. This particular named is best handled with at least one full group, since there can be massive BAF in the area. Relog pulling may be possible, but it’s difficult due to the respawn rate in the area. <br>
 <br>
Green Knight: Though he is technically in Forest Sauvage, this monster is on the zone border between the zones and actually moves between them during combat. The difficulty equivalent of the Glacier Giant and Evern, he’s quite difficult, and probably requires about the same number of people as the Grand Summoner. Due to his high melee damage, speed, and styles, the fatality rate will probably be higher, however. The Green Knight teleports fairly frequently, making combat that much more confusing. He also summons trees, which typically con yellow at level 50, and casts a low damage heat Area of Effect Spell. He is capable of healing himself, and parries quite frequently. Overall, a fairly difficult encounter, but he is easily accessible from the mainland. This makes him much more convenient to gather people for than most Epic Monsters. <br>
<br>
Rewards for the Green Knight: The Green Knight drops Quality 93% gear, with particle effects for the weapons. This is not necessarily sufficient for the difficulty of his encounter, but probably necessary to balance how easy he is to reach from the mainland. <br>
